1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,715
Now let's take a look at how we can calculate

2

00:00:02,715  -->  00:00:06,360
validation_loss for our model during training.

3

00:00:06,360  -->  00:00:12,670
To do this, we first need to split our dataset into training and validation_dataset.

4

00:00:12,670  -->  00:00:15,180
For this, we tokenize input text,

5

00:00:15,180  -->  00:00:16,760
just as we did before,

6

00:00:16,760  -->  00:00:22,620
and then we calculate how many tokens we want to use for training given this ratio.

7

00:00:22,620  -->  00:00:25,820
We take this number of tokens as a training data,

8

00:00:25,820  -->  00:00:29,415
and then we use the rest as validation_data.

9

00:00:29,415  -->  00:00:31,935
Having training and validation_data,

10

00:00:31,935  -->  00:00:34,245
we then create a validation_dataset,

11

00:00:34,245  -->  00:00:37,115
and then we create a validation_dataloader.

12

00:00:37,115  -->  00:00:41,490
Now we need to implement a function to calculate a validation_loss.

13

00:00:41,490  -->  00:00:43,350
For this, we, first of all,

14

00:00:43,350  -->  00:00:47,410
switch our model from training into the evaluation mode.

15

00:00:47,410  -->  00:00:51,430
We should do this to run our model for inference, and this,

16

00:00:51,430  -->  00:00:56,990
for example, deactivates the dropout layers we've added to our model.

17

00:00:56,990  -->  00:01:00,150
Keep in mind that then we switch our model to

18

00:01:00,150  -->  00:01:04,170
the training mode at the beginning of every training iteration.

19

00:01:04,170  -->  00:01:08,330
We then create an iterator from our validation_dataset.

20

00:01:08,330  -->  00:01:11,920
Then we run the loop for the specified number of batches,

21

00:01:11,920  -->  00:01:13,150
and for every batch,

22

00:01:13,150  -->  00:01:17,845
we do similar steps comparing to what we've done for the training.

23

00:01:17,845  -->  00:01:20,670
We, first of all, get the inputs and targets.

24

00:01:20,670  -->  00:01:25,050
We then pass these inputs to the model and get logits.

25

00:01:25,050  -->  00:01:27,870
Then we reshape logits and targets,

26

00:01:27,870  -->  00:01:32,830
and calculate the validation_loss using the cross_entropy function.

27

00:01:32,830  -->  00:01:38,330
After this, we add the loss to the validation_loss on every iteration.

28

00:01:38,330  -->  00:01:39,770
When the loop is finished,

29

00:01:39,770  -->  00:01:42,810
we compute the average_loss by dividing

30

00:01:42,810  -->  00:01:46,250
the total_loss by the number of batches we went through,

31

00:01:46,250  -->  00:01:48,730
and then we return the average_loss.

32

00:01:48,730  -->  00:01:54,295
Finally, we need to update our code to draw a chart of training and validation_losses.

33

00:01:54,295  -->  00:01:59,550
First, we need to append training loss and training step to these two arrays,

34

00:01:59,550  -->  00:02:04,400
and we need to use the item method to convert a tensor to a number,

35

00:02:04,400  -->  00:02:07,195
and we do it for every training step.

36

00:02:07,195  -->  00:02:10,765
Then we need to do the same for the validation_loss.

37

00:02:10,765  -->  00:02:16,080
The reason why we need to store step number with loss values is because we calculate

38

00:02:16,080  -->  00:02:21,635
training loss on every step and validation_loss only every 10 steps,

39

00:02:21,635  -->  00:02:24,240
and we need to preserve step numbers for

40

00:02:24,240  -->  00:02:29,405
the Matplotlib to correctly plot these charts and align values correctly.

41

00:02:29,405  -->  00:02:31,320
I'll now rerun this notebook.

42

00:02:31,320  -->  00:02:35,600
As you can see, we've got our training and validation_loss chart,

43

00:02:35,600  -->  00:02:38,620
and if we wait for a few dozen iterations,

44

00:02:38,620  -->  00:02:41,040
we will now see two lines on the chart,

45

00:02:41,040  -->  00:02:46,280
one for the train loss and another for the validation_loss.
